&lt;p&gt;Join us for an unforgettable evening at the Horn of Africa Fundraising Gala, hosted by the Somali Student Association and Ethiopian Eritrean Student Association. Together, we aim to support the communities in East Africa that have been deeply impacted by climate change, war, and famine. Many of our student members from countries around the horn of Africa&amp;nbsp;and beyond have personal ties to these challenges, and we are coming together to help raise funds to provide essential resources and support initiatives that address these pressing issues. Your participation and contributions will make a meaningful impact in improving lives and building resilience within these communities.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The gala will feature inspiring performances, speakers, and dancing, celebrating the vibrant cultures of the Horn of Africa while raising critical funds for ARAHA (American Relief Agency for the Horn of Africa). ARAHA provides essential resources such as food, clean water, and education to communities across East Africa, ensuring hope and resilience in the face of ongoing humanitarian crises. ALL ticket proceeds will be donated to ARAHA.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The event will consist of inspiring speakers, film presentations, dance performances, clothing/accessory/food vendors and more. All members of the immediate and extended Columbia community are welcome to attend. Dinner will be provided. Please dress your best! Cultural attire is encouraged.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We can&amp;#39;t wait to see you all!!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This event celebrates the dynamic interdisciplinary community of past and present Presidential Scholars in Society and Neuroscience (PSSN), showcasing the program&amp;#39;s intellectual and institutional impact at the intersection of neuroscience and society.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Through presentations and discussion, past and current Scholars will reflect on how their research projects&amp;mdash;guided by faculty mentors across Columbia University&amp;rsquo;s campuses&amp;mdash;have shaped the evolution of the study of mind, brain, and society. Together, they will explore how the unique initiative of the Presidential Scholars in Society and Neuroscience Program has served as a catalyst for groundbreaking work and continues to influence their professional endeavors.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This gathering offers a platform to reconnect with peers, share research and experiences, and strengthen a network of scholars addressing some of society&amp;#39;s most pressing challenges. Join us to celebrate the program&amp;rsquo;s legacy, highlight the achievements of its alumni, and envision the future of interdisciplinary collaboration in neuroscience and beyond.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Event Information&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Free and open to the public. &lt;a href="https://www.eventbrite.com/e/mind-brain-and-society-presidential-scholars-in-conversation-tickets-1216684278429" target="_blank"&gt;Registration&lt;/a&gt; required. Please contact &lt;a href="mailto:presidentialscholars@columbia.edu"&gt;presidentialscholars@columbia.edu&lt;/a&gt; with any questions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This event is hosted by &lt;a href="https://scienceandsociety.columbia.edu/content/presidential-scholars-society-and-neuroscience"&gt;Presidential Scholars in Society and Neuroscience&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Center for Science and Society makes every reasonable effort to accommodate individuals with disabilities. If you require disability accommodations to attend a Center for Science and Society event, please contact us at &lt;a href="mailto:scienceandsociety@columbia.edu"&gt;scienceandsociety@columbia.edu&lt;/a&gt; or (212) 853-1612 at least 10 days in advance of the event. For more information, please visit the &lt;a href="https://eoaa.columbia.edu/content/accessibility" target="_blank"&gt;campus accessibility webpage&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Join the Institute for Israel and Jewish Studies &amp;amp; The Naomi Foundation on &lt;strong&gt;Monday, March 3, at noon&lt;/strong&gt;, for the &lt;strong&gt;2024-2025 Naomi Prawer Kadar Annual Memorial Lecture&lt;/strong&gt; with Professor &lt;strong&gt;Hannah Pollin-Galay, &lt;/strong&gt;Tel Aviv University; Yale University (2024-2025). This talk, titled &amp;ldquo;Turning Holocaust Slang into Art: Between K. Tzetnik and Chava Rosenfarb,&amp;rdquo; will take place virtually via Zoom.&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Yiddish language drastically changed in the ghettos and camps of Nazi Europe. By one estimate, roughly 3,000 new words and phrases were added to the language. Many of these neologisms were of a vulgar nature, relating to topics like theft and sex work. While some people found these new words embarrassing, unseemly and just plain ugly, others attempted to uplift them and transform them into art. Among the writers that incorporated Khurbn Yiddish (Yiddish of the Holocaust), into their postwar poetry and prose, the authors K. Tzetnik and Chava Rosenfarb stand out. Each extracted and presented the aesthetic potential of Khurbn Yiddish words in different ways.&amp;nbsp; K. Tzetnik emphasized the horrifying, bizarre side of Khurbn Yiddish words, molding them into an expressionistic scream. Rosenfarb, by contrast, shined a light onto the small acts of resilience contained within Khurbn Yiddish words, memories of self-expression and communication against the odds. Her ghetto terms become beautiful in the way they invite readers into scenes of everyday life under Nazi rule, moments from the margins of history that are rarely considered worthy of notice. The two authors also clash on the topic of female sexuality&amp;mdash;and the ways that words relate to the body.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hannah Pollin-Galay&lt;/strong&gt; is Associate Professor in the Department of Literature at Tel Aviv University, where she is also Head of the&lt;a href="https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https://humanities.tau.ac.il/goldreich/&amp;amp;data=05%257C02%257Ceuropean.studies@yale.edu%257C811ae3e29fa74d42ac6a08dcc7932810%257Cdd8cbebb21394df8b4114e3e87abeb5c%257C0%257C0%257C638604682069162377%257CUnknown%257CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0=%257C0%257C%257C%257C&amp;amp;sdata=5YzqhiVPVL+l+/lV1WaMvKM0Fpa0eJE+RSQSFIE3XJ0=&amp;amp;reserved=0"&gt; &lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href="https://en-humanities.tau.ac.il/goldreich"&gt;Jona Goldrich Institute for Yiddish Language, Literature and Culture&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp;In addition to being a 2024-2025 Senior Scholar at the Fortunoff Archive for Holocaust Testimony at Yale University, Pollin-Galay is also a Yiddish Book Center Translation Fellow, where she is translating Yiddish ecopoetry from the Holocaust.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.eventbrite.com/e/the-2025-kadar-lecture-with-hannah-pollin-galay-tickets-1109404983169?aff=oddtdtcreator" target="_blank"&gt;CLICK HERE TO REGISTER FOR THIS EVENT&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
