&lt;p&gt;Part talk, part screening, this experimental presentation makes its way into the question of law and crime through a master-film of the jurisprudential genre little known in the Anglo-American context.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;El Chacal de Nahueltoro&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;(Miguel Litt&amp;iacute;n, 1969) is no ordinary object.&amp;nbsp;With its complex negotiation of the fabula/syuzhet distinction, it dramatizes the 1960 case of a peasant man who kills a woman and five of her daughters in a rural part of Chile. Exploring the critical possibilities of the videographic essay, the presentation is as much a methodological provocation as it is a jurisprudential one.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Please note: this talk lecture and title were updated on February 14, 2025&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Speaker&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href="https://cms.uchicago.edu/people/salome-aguilera-skvirsky" target="_blank"&gt;Salom&amp;eacute; Aguilera Skvirsky&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is an Associate Professor in the Department of Cinema and Media Studies at the University of Chicago. Her first book,&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;The Process Genre: Cinema and the Aesthetic of Labor&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;(Duke University Press, 2020), won the 2021 Best First Book Prize from the Society for Cinema and Media Studies. Her essays have appeared in&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Cinema Journal&lt;/em&gt;, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Journal of Latin American Cultural Studies, Social Identities, Hispan&amp;oacute;fila,&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;and in&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;The Routledge Companion to Latin American Cinema.&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;Skvirsky&amp;rsquo;s current project, &amp;ldquo;Filming the Police,&amp;rdquo; is supported by a Howard Foundation grant and a Mellon New Directions fellowship and involves formal training in legal studies.&lt;/p&gt;
